DNS Port Conflict: Pi-hole vs Nginx (WordPress)

## Overview
This project documents the complete troubleshooting and resolution of a port conflict between a Docker-based Pi-hole (DNS filtering) and Nginx (WordPress) on an Ubuntu server.

## The Problem
- WordPress site (Nginx) was inaccessible
- Pi-hole's web interface was also inaccessible
- Server required daily reboots to temporarily fix glitching
- Root cause: Both services were trying to use **port 80** simultaneously

## Symptoms Observed
- `systemctl status nginx` showed: `code=killed, signal=KILL`
- Pi-hole container was running but web interface unreachable
- Port 80 was bound to `docker-proxy` (Pi-hole) but Nginx also needed it

## Diagnostic Steps

### 1. Check what's using port 80
```bash
sudo ss -tulpn | grep :80
```

Output: Showed docker-proxy using port 80 (Pi-hole container)

2. Check Nginx status

```bash
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

Output: failed (Result: signal) with code=killed, signal=KILL

3. Identify the container name

```bash
docker ps
```

Container name: pihole-unbound

4. Check Pi-hole container logs

```bash
docker logs pihole-unbound --tail 50
```

Output: Confirmed FTL was listening internally but port not accessible externally

The Solution

Step 1: Stop and remove the existing container (data preserved in volumes)

```bash
docker stop pihole-unbound
docker rm pihole-unbound
```

Step 2: Recreate the container with port 8080 for web interface

```bash
docker run -d \
  --name pihole-unbound \
  --restart unless-stopped \
  -p 53:53/tcp -p 53:53/udp \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -v pihole-data:/etc/pihole \
  -v dnsmasq-data:/etc/dnsmasq.d \
  -e TZ="America/Chicago" \
  -e WEBPASSWORD="Anuserver327" \
  pihole/pihole:latest
```

Step 3: Restart Nginx

```bash
sudo systemctl restart nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
```

Final Working Configuration

Service Port Access URL
WordPress (Nginx) 80 http://192.168.1.139
Pi-hole DNS 53 (UDP/TCP) (background service)
Pi-hole Admin 8080 http://192.168.1.139:8080/admin

Additional Improvements Made

Set memory limit to prevent crashes

```bash
docker update --memory=512m --memory-swap=1g pihole-unbound
```

Added Docker auto-restart policy

Already included in run command: --restart unless-stopped

Configured Pi-hole blocklists and regex filters

· Added regex patterns for ad servers, telemetry, analytics, trackers
· Block rate achieved: 89.7% of DNS queries

Set up automated gravity updates (cron)

```bash
(crontab -l 2>/dev/null; echo "0 2 * * * /usr/bin/docker exec pihole-unbound pihole -g") | crontab -
```

Lessons Learned

Linux / System Administration

· ss -tulpn is essential for diagnosing port conflicts
· systemctl status reveals why a service failed
· Port conflicts cause cascading failures (Nginx killed, web interfaces down)

Docker

· Docker containers cannot change port mappings without recreating them
· Data volumes (-v) preserve configuration across container removal
· docker inspect --format='{{.LogPath}}' finds container logs
· --restart unless-stopped ensures container survives reboots/crashes

Port Planning

· Default ports (80, 443) should go to primary web server
· Ancillary services (admin panels) should use alternate ports (8080, 8443)

